{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486876","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486876"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:47:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:47:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"196"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"196","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/196"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.68,0.15,0.03,0.1,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"196"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76740"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"196","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/196"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"196"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62233"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"240"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12334"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42025"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76740","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76740"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 18-year old man presents to the Emergency Department with a six-hour history of severe epigastric pain. This started soon after a bout of vomiting - which he attributes to eating an old pizza last night during a night of heavy drinking. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 100/70mmHg, SpO2 94% on room air and temperature 37.4\u00b0C. There are areas of subcutaneous crepitation on palpation of the base of his neck and dullness to percussion at the left base of his chest with no breath sounds heard in this region. He is tender in the epigastrium and the rest of the abdomen is soft.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Boerhaave syndrome","Mallory-Weiss tear","Tracheal tear","Ruptured pulmonary bullous","Bronchial rupture"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECrepitations under the skin indicates the presence of air. The air will have either come from the respiratory or digestive tract. Whilst rupture of the oesophagus is a rare event, it is typically associated with vomiting - particularly if the patient attempts to suppress the urge to vomit. In other words, there is an episode of barotrauma, with increased intra-oesophageal pressure as food is forced up the oesophagus against a closed glottis. However, this cannot be assumed, and the crepitations could well be the result of the rupture of a pulmonary bullous or bleb. Many such cases that were previously assumed to be due to an oesophageal rupture are more likely to be due to air from a\u003Cstrong\u003E ruptured pulmonary bleb/bullous\u003C/strong\u003E. These small pockets of air are often found in young, healthy individuals with no medical issues. Heavy exertion (exercise or vomiting) may cause one of these blebs to rupture - leading to a clinical picture resembling oesophageal rupture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this particular case however, the dullness at the left base of the chest suggests that the underlying problem is more likely to be a ruptured oesophagus with a collection of gastric contents in the pleural space (\u003Cstrong\u003EBoerhaave syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E). A ruptured oesophagus is the more serious and - life threatening - potential cause of this clinical picture and this diagnosis must always be assumed until proven otherwise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA patient with a \u003Cstrong\u003EMallory-Weiss tear \u003C/strong\u003Eis most likely to present with a haematemesis and as these lesions involve the oesophageal mucosa only, would not spill gastric contents into the pleural space.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Etracheal tear\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare event and when seen, usually occurs at the result of blunt or penetrating trauma. Similarly, bronchial rupture is uncommon and is usually the result of trauma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Subcutaneous air in the neck or chest after a bout of forceful vomiting must always raise the possibility of oesophageal rupture."],"references":["Shenfine J, Griffin SM. Oesophageal rupture. Br J Hosp Med (Lond). 2007 Feb;68(2):M18-21. doi: 10.12968/hmed.2007.68.Sup2.22838. PMID: 17370707. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17370707/","Turner AR, Collier SA, Turner SD. Boerhaave Syndrome. 2023 Dec 4. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28613559.","Chew FY, Yang ST. Boerhaave syndrome. CMAJ. 2021 Sep 27;193(38):E1499. doi: 10.1503/cmaj.202893. PMID: 34580144; PMCID: PMC8486476."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62233"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"196"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62233","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62233"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-04T19:51:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-04T19:51:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"196"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76740"}}